Recommendations:
We recommend that the City Accountant:
Direct the conduct a thorough review and analysis of all outstanding accounts payable;
Proposed for the reversion to the general fund all long-outstanding payables/balances of accounts, aged three (3) to sixteen (16) years if warranted and/or unsupported Accounts Payables and effect the necessary adjustments/journal entries;
Conduct a regular review and monitoring of all booked obligations to ensure that only valid claims remain in the books; and
Direct the accounting in-charge to update the subsidiary ledgers regularly and reconcile the balances with the general ledger.

1)  We recommended that management require the CSWDO to:

submit copy of the uploaded SAC data and the SAC forms of the 1,848 beneficiaries; otherwise, the total amount of P11,088,000.00 shall be suspended in audit; and

submit justification on the 24,668 mis-targeted beneficiaries specifically the 20,692 with wrong supporting documents; 2,910 with lacking data presented in their SAC forms; and the 1,066 unqualified beneficiaries;

 Three (3) LGU Tagum workers to refund the P18,000.00 cash subsidy received; otherwise, the same would be charged to those responsible for their inclusion;



  CSWDO/Punong Barangays concerned to submit their respective certification for the 127 recipients beneficiaries that: they belong to a low-income family; do not belong to a 4Ps household; none of the member(s) of his/her family falls within the exclusion; and how much monthly amount of honorarium they receive from their respective barangays;

Cash subsidy of 934 recipients who are private employees to submit certification from their respective employers/DOLE that: they are “no work no pay” during the ECQ periods; and that they did not receive any cash subsidy under the DOLE amelioration program;



Recipient two (2) pensioners to submit SSS/CSWDO certification that they did not receive any pension during the ECQ periods; and

We also recommended that management maintain an updated database of Tagum City residents through better coordination with Puroks and Barangays to properly identify possible beneficiaries of social amelioration programs of the government and accurately expedite the delivery of the same.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Secure from the Sangguniang Panlungsod a resolution granting him authority to accept the P68,423,800.86 donations from various sources for Covid-19-related purposes, to ratify the contracts of donations entered into by him in behalf of CGT;

Instruct the City’s responsible officials that all payments, including donations, in favor of CGT shall be receipted immediately by the CTO;



Instruct the personnel authorized by him or the CDRRMO and CBO to facilitate the use of the Cash Donation Utilization Request (CDUR) before any cash donations are utilized as required under Annex A of COA Circular No. 2014-002;



Instruct the City’s responsible officials that payments out of the cash donations shall be made through the issuance of check based on duly approved disbursement vouchers pursuant to COA Circular 2014-002;

Instruct the CBO to prepare and maintain the Registry of Cash Donations and Utilization (RCDU) to record the donations per donor per purpose as required under Annex B of COA Circular No. 2014-002; and



Instruct the CGSO and CSWDO to submit the lacking duly acknowledged distribution lists for the P1,123,980 welfare goods, P1,696,798.00 food supplies, and P3,458,551.90 office, medical and other supplies distributed as detailed in Annex A of this AOM.



We also recommended that the CACCO:

Demand from the Donations and Sponsorship Team/Admin and Support Group of the CCTF the liquidation of the P786,557.00 cash donations claimed to have been already utilized;

Prepare and maintain separate subsidiary ledger (SL) for "Trust Liabilities- DRRMF" (Annex C of COA Circular No. 2014-002) for cash donations received amounting to P100,000.00 and above per donor per purpose while those below P100,000.00 shall be grouped and posted in one SL labeled as "Various Donors" per purpose;

Recognize in the books the P295,000.00 donated PPE as detailed in Annex A of this AOM and accordingly, prepare and maintain PPE Ledger Cards for all donated PPE;

Disclose in the Notes to FS a) the P812,000.00 total cash donations received; b)the correct amount of P68,272,420.86 in-kind donations received; c) the total inventories procured, issued, and balances sourced out from the BGCM funds and cash donations; and d) the PPE procured out of the Bayanihan Grant and cash donations as well as the donated PPE and the disposal or transfer, if any;

Refrain from recognizing in the books in-kind donations but disclosed only the same in the Notes to FS; and

Demand from the CLYDO the accounting of cash donations it collected, if any, which was coursed through the private accounts of one its job order personnel.



We further recommended that the CGSO:
Prepare the AR for In-Kind Donations for DRRM (Annex D of COA Circular No. 2014-002) and have the same signed by the City Mayor or his authorized representative and the donor for every receipt of in-kind donations;

Prepare and issue PARs for the P295,000.00 donated PPE as well as the ICS for those P114,697.00 small items with useful life of more than one year, copy furnish the Audit Team; and

Submit to the NDRRMC, through the Office of the Civil Defense, a one-time report showing separately the cash donations and in-kind donations received by the City for the Covid-19.

1.  We recommended that the Accountant conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the receivables and continuously send demand letters to all concerned to enforce collection of the dormant accounts;

2. We also recommended that the Accountant take appropriate action for accounts which balances remained inactive or non-moving in the books of accounts for 10 years or more and where settlement or collectability is remote by requesting for write-off of these accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005;



3.We likewise recommended that the Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entry to recognize the impairment loss on receivables in accordance with the Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards (PPSAS).

We recommended that:
The ACBOS furnish the City Auditor’s Office with all Contracts of Sale and Memorandums of Agreement in relation to the sale of asphalting products and services to its prospective clients within five working days from execution of contracts/memorandums as required under Section 3 of COA Circular No. 2009-001;

2. The Asphalt Management and Advisory Committee formulate a reasonable estimate in the appropriation of annual budget for the asphalting operations;

The ACBOS strive to generate more projects for its Asphalting Operations to generate much-needed revenues through maximum utilization of the available appropriation under its disposal;




The Asphalt Management and Advisory Committee thoroughly supervise and monitor the implementation of asphalting projects to mitigate and/or prevent the deficiencies noted such as delay in project implementation;

The Asphalt Management and Advisory Committee, when dictated by specific circumstances, immediately propose to the Sangguniang Panlungsod any revision on matters relating to the costing and selling prices of the goods offered by the ACBOS;

The Sangguniang Panlungsod pass a local tax ordinance which shall include the specific guidelines and policies in determining contract price, cost of the project, and classification of services offered by the Asphalt and Concrete Batching Plant; and

The ACBOS submit immediately a written justification of the incurrence of delay in the delivery of four HMA asphalting projects to LGU-Panabo City.

We reiterated the CY 2015 recommendations to be undertaken by the City: 

1. We recommended that the Sangguniang Panlungsod pass a local tax ordinance which includes specific guidelines and policies in determining contract price, cost of the project and classification of services offered by the Asphalt and Concrete Batching Plant;

2. We also recommended that the Asphalt Marketing and Advisory Committee, when dictated by specific circumstances propose to the Sangguniang Panlungsod any revision on matters relating to the costing and selling prices of the goods offered by the Asphalt Concrete and Batching Plant; 

3. We further recommended that the ACBOS furnish the COA Office and CACCO with the list of unpaid balance of accounts of customers from Private, NGOs, NGAs and LGUs on completed projects with its corresponding certificates of completion and the actual cost incurred classified per HMA products for CY 2017 and 2018, to facilitate recording thereof to appropriate accounts;

4. We likewise recommended that the CACCO shall record the revenue and income from the asphalt operations in conformance with PPSAS No. 9; and 

5. Lastly, we recommended that the City Treasurer require each payee to present an order of payment/billing statement from the CEO as basis to collect the specific amount due to the City and open a separate bank account for the Asphalt and Concrete Batching Plant as provided in Section 9.1 of City Ordinance No. 13, s.-2001.

We recommended that Management require the recipients-NGOs/POs to immediately liquidate the funds transferred to them. If necessary, impose sanctions to the delinquent NGOs/POs, as provided in Section 9.0 of COA Circular 2007-001; 

Also, we recommended that Management require the accreditation of the NGO/PO and submission of documentary requirements to Sangguniang Panlungsod to be eligible for the fund transfer; and 

Finally, we recommended that Management communicate with the Local Chief Executives of the Provinces of Bohol and Leyte as well as the Medical Center Chief of Southern Philippine Medical Center and request for the liquidation of the funds transferred to them.

We recommended that the LCE require the Inventory Committee to conduct proper planning in undertaking the physical count of PPE and inventories recorded in the books of the City, so as not to compromise the submission of the RPCPPE to be submitted before January 31 of the succeeding year;

Also, we recommended that Management submit the RPCPPE for CY 2018 to the Office of City Auditor;

Moreover, we recommended that department heads assigned to monitor the status of implementation of the trust fund projects shall prepare a status report on Trust Fund projects and submit to the Local Chief Executive as basis for the latter to issue a Certificate of Completion and Acceptance for completed Trust Fund projects; and

Finally, we recommended that the City Accountant consider the transfer PPE accounts from the trust fund to the general fund and recognize depreciation expenses in each PPE accounts.

We recommended that the City Economic Enterprises (CEE) Manager shall initiate a re-measurement of all stalls in the public market and use the actual measurement of the area in the computation of the rental rate per sq.m./day, to be fair to all stallholders concerned;


We also enjoined the CEE Manager to look into the current stall rental rate/sq.m./day used for each section of the market and make the necessary adjustments, as applicable; 

Finally, we recommended that the CEE shall endeavor to install a computer system that could simplify the processes involved in maintaining a data base for all the relevant information about the 1,080 stallholders such as name of lessees and other personal information, date of award of stall, history of transfers from former to current lessees, stall number, market section, actual area in sq.m., rental rate/sq.m./day,  rental payments ledger and other pertinent information, including a link to the location map where a particular stall is located.

We recommended that the LCE form a fact-finding committee to conduct investigation on the destruction/damages made on Crisis Center Building at Barangay Magdum and determine the persons responsible and accountable, subject to administrative and criminal liability and instruct the committee to furnish COA a copy of their final report;

Also, we recommended that the LCE instruct the SMO to provide a security personnel to safeguard the Crisis Center Building and all identified infrastructure projects not yet occupied and turned-over to end-user/department;

Moreover, we recommended that the CEO prioritize and expedite the completion of the Crisis Center Building at Barangay Magdum and for offices concerned, GAD and CEO, to continue to monitor the repairs on damaged parts and its completion;

Finally, we recommended that the LCE consider implementing some projects by contract, if necessary, to fast track the completion and delivery of services to the intended beneficiaries.

Submit written justification for undertaking the projects by administration knowing that the prerequisite conditions/cases provided under Section 3.3 of Appendix 1 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 were not present when the City implemented the projects;

Submit the relevant documents to support that the City is capable of implementing the projects by administration such as experience or track record relevant to the projects, list of professional, technical & experienced personnel to undertake, supervise and manage the projects, list of equipment owned by the City to be used in the projects;

Copy of Approved Annual Procurement Plan showing the inclusion of the projects to be undertaken by administration; and 


Submit written authority from the President for the project undertaken by administration costing P190.7 Million and written authority from the Secretary of DPWH for the projects costing P20 Million to P50 Million, otherwise the disbursements/expenditures shall be suspended or disallowed in audit as the case maybe.

We recommended that the City Economic Enterprises (CEE) Manager shall set a target to reduce the stall rental receivables and strategize on how to improve its collection efficiency; 

We also recommended that the CEE Manager shall endeavor to promptly issue statements of accounts or demand letters as soon as accounts become due and demandable;

We likewise recommended that the CEE Manager shall look into the circumstances where stallholders whose contracts of lease were not renewed still continue to operate their businesses at the public market.

Strictly ensure that all job order employees reporting at the new city hall to register their daily attendance on the biometric machine;

Maintain an updated logbook for every department/office that will be regularly checked/inspected by the HRMO;

Require the employees assigned on the field to use the bundy clock for the establishment of a reliable number of days worked as the basis for the computation of their wages; and

Ensure that employees who leave the office, either for personal or official reasons secure a duly signed pass slips from their supervisor.

We reiterated the prior year’s recommendation that the management should:

1. Maximize the utilization of the LDRRMF from current year’s appropriation and prior years’ unexpended balance to enable the City to implement projects related to disaster prevention, mitigation and preparedness within the scheduled timeframe; 

2. Expedite the implementation of all PPAs under LDRRM to prevent possible loss of life, damage to government and private property, and loss of livelihood;

3. Submit a detailed Accomplishment Report for CY 2018 to the Audit Team for proper evaluation of the activities conducted and projects implemented by the CDRRMO.

We recommended that CARCHO expedite the preparation of POW for 20% Development Fund infrastructure projects in the succeeding year;


We also recommended that Management should avoid unprogrammed appropriations or lump-sum appropriations and identify specific PPAs in the AIP, as well as allocate the budget to be funded under explicit areas of development/office by indicating the corresponding project cost, necessary fund flows to approximate the reasonable timing in the release of funds and period of implementation;

Moreover, we recommended that Management should require the CPDO, CARCHO and CEO and other offices concerned in the implementation to improve the planning, scheduling of work activities and manpower in order to facilitate the timely completion of the projects. Submit a concrete time-plan to serve as a basis in gauging actual accomplishments while planning of the projects to be implemented should be completed before the start of the year; and

Finally, consider implementing some projects by contract, if necessary, to fast track the completion and delivery of services to the intended beneficiaries.

1.	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) of the City conduct a meeting with the CVO, as the implementing department and the MNLF organization as beneficiary of the PAMANA program, and require from the organization a strategic/contingency plan to sustain the program; 

We also recommended that the LCE remind the MNLF members/beneficiaries to religiously abide by the provision stated in the MOA and project proposal especially on the matter of re-dispersing the original stocks if an offspring had been produced and require them to submit financial reports and status of dispersed animals; and 

3. Also, we recommended that the CVO as implementing department, to continue to assess, monitor and make preventive and corrective actions to sustain the life of the remaining dispersed animals with the MNLF beneficiaries.

We recommended that the implementing department concerned make a thorough study and identify projects that are feasible and not include projects which had history of failure to avoid cancellation/dropping of projects;

We recommended that Management amend its purchase request and coordinate with the supplier to prioritize the delivery of the specific kind of Bamboo (Kawayang Tinik/ Tongcan), to CSO beneficiaries in order that the BUB project may be implemented;

We also recommended that the offices concerned handling the BUB project to coordinate with CSO beneficiaries and procure the exact specifications of requested materials so as not to delay the implementation of the BUB project; and 

4. Finally, we recommended that the unexpended balance of dropped/cancelled BuB projects be returned to the source agency as soon as possible.

We recommended that Management require the supplier to submit the lacking compliance certifications and other requirements related to the delivery of cattle and goats. Otherwise, the disbursement shall be suspended in audit;

We recommended that Management submit a written justification relative to the loss of the goats stating therein the preventive measures undertaken, post-action on the implementation the program and action taken against the supplier; and

We recommended that Management revisit the MOA on the PAMANA Program to properly implement the program to the benefit of the intended beneficiaries.

We recommended that Management prioritize and make necessary actions to facilitate the implementation of the projects/programs so that the CSO beneficiaries may enjoy the benefits, avoid the incurrence of penalty deductions and project termination;

We also recommended that the offices concerned CAGRO and CVO together with the CSO beneficiaries make necessary actions to comply with the documentary requirements needed for the implementation of the BuB projects/programs; and

Finally, we recommended that the unexpended balance of dropped/cancelled BuB programs/projects shall be returned back to the source agency as early as possible.

We recommended that Management:

Avoid lump-sum appropriation and identify specific PPAs in the AIP and allocation of budget to be funded under explicit areas of development/office indicating the corresponding project cost, necessary fund flows to approximate the reasonable timing in the release of funds and period of implementation;

Direct the offices concerned to prepare the necessary POWs for implementation of the P26.11M appropriated projects which remained unimplemented;

Require the barangays to strictly comply with the submission of the BDPs to serve as a tool in project identification of the city;

Require the CPDO, CARCHO and CEO and other offices concerned in the implementation to improve the planning and scheduling of work activities and manpower in order to facilitate timely completion of the projects. Submit a concrete time-plan to serve as a basis in gauging actual accomplishments. Planning of the projects to be implemented should be completed before the start of the year for implementation;

Consider implementing some projects by contract, if necessary, to fast track the completion and delivery of services to the intended beneficiaries.

We recommended that management should:

Maximize the utilization of the LDRRMF from current year’s appropriation and prior years’ unexpended balance to enable the City to implement projects related to disaster prevention, mitigation and preparedness within the scheduled timeframe; 

Expedite the implementation of all PPAs under LDRRM to prevent possible loss of life, damage to government and private property, and loss of livelihood;

Avoid “un-programmed” appropriations and identify specific PPAs in the LDRRMFIP to approximate the reasonable timing in the release of funds and period of implementation.

We recommended that Management:

Strengthen the SWM IEC through implementation of the specific programs/ projects enumerated under the SWMP of the City;

Revisit those programs and projects which are not viable and find alternative means to achieve the identified targets;


Enjoin all barangays to actively participate in the implementation of the SWMP and have functional MRFs and emphasize the prompt submission of required reports. As a consequence, non-complying barangays may not be given their financial aid allocation; 

Consider addressing all the recommendations noted by the survey respondents on the garbage collection procedures of the CENRO; and

Enforce strictly the segregation at source to ensure compliance with the SWMP.

The CACCO and the CEO shall reconcile their records to determine the status and correct balances of the affected CIP accounts (Refer to Annex R for the details of completed project lodged in CIP accounts);

The CGSO shall submit Utilization reports and CEO shall provide the CACCO with Certificate of Completion and Acceptance of all completed projects to cause the transfer of these projects from CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts; and

Based on the adjusted data, the City Accounting Office compute for the required depreciation on the completed projects, and accordingly adjust the balances of the affected accounts.

